<div id="review_1104401826" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1104401826" />
    <a title="Claire Banschbach" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27580255-claire-banschbach"><img alt="Claire Banschbach" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1465524360p2/27580255.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1104401826?book_show_action=true">Nov 12, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Claire Banschbach" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Claire Banschbach" href="/user/show/27580255-claire-banschbach">Claire Banschbach</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1104401826" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4250018342928543037">This was a good story with a very interesting premise. I just didn&apos;t care for it as much as others. Partly I think because I&apos;m not really &quot;into&quot; the YA/Dystopian genre. <br/><br/>Don&apos;t get me wrong, it&apos;s a brilliant premise and the author is an amazing writer. It&apos;s just that the first half of the book dragged really slowly for me. And I spend much of the time being frustrated with the heroine (as seems fairly standard with this genre). Half the time I wanted to smack her for whining about how she had wast</span>
  <span id="freeText4250018342928543037" style="display:none">This was a good story with a very interesting premise. I just didn't care for it as much as others. Partly I think because I'm not really "into" the YA/Dystopian genre. <br /><br />Don't get me wrong, it's a brilliant premise and the author is an amazing writer. It's just that the first half of the book dragged really slowly for me. And I spend much of the time being frustrated with the heroine (as seems fairly standard with this genre). Half the time I wanted to smack her for whining about how she had wasted her life and only had one year left to live, and the rest of the time for making extremely questionable decisions once she was on the other side of the Wall. As in <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ if you meet a guy who seems familiar with the scary world on the other side of the wall, why are you whining about how he won't take you to some city (that he clearly doesn't like/trust) and then proceed to jump on a train and leave him in the middle of nowhere? You'd think he might know what he's talking about. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />The second half of the book really picked up and I didn't put it down. It was a bit predictable but I was still glued to the book to see how the events would unfold. <br /><br />I don't think I liked it as much since I haven't been part of the YA targeted age group for several years and I've recently come to the conclusion that Dystopian is not my favorite genre. <br /><br />BUT<br /><br />If you like this genre and are looking for a story with action, adventure, and solid Christian themes, then please pick up this book!! <br /><i>I realize my review sounds a little negative, but it's more of a "it's not you, it's me" thing. A lot of other people I know love this book, so definitely try it out! :) </i> </span>
  <a data-text-id="4250018342928543037" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

