    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2844965102" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2844965102" />
    <a title="Mazzy Mitchell" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/97934393-mazzy-mitchell"><img alt="Mazzy Mitchell" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1619149388p2/97934393.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2844965102?book_show_action=true">Mar 04, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mazzy Mitchell" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mazzy Mitchell" href="/user/show/97934393-mazzy-mitchell">Mazzy Mitchell</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/97934393-mazzy-mitchell?shelf=2021">2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2844965102" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7530308559386992961">If I was supposed to collect about my thoughts about this book, then I didn&apos;t, because I started the sequel on the next day. Overall, I think there are some parts of this book that are absolutely excellent, and some parts whose pieces could have fit together better. <br/><br/>As to plot, it&apos;s pretty fast-moving, perhaps with the occasional hole here or there, but not any glaring issues, although knowing that there were two more books to come kind of kept me from utter trepidation? As to characters, Parvin</span>
  <span id="freeText7530308559386992961" style="display:none">If I was supposed to collect about my thoughts about this book, then I didn't, because I started the sequel on the next day. Overall, I think there are some parts of this book that are absolutely excellent, and some parts whose pieces could have fit together better. <br /><br />As to plot, it's pretty fast-moving, perhaps with the occasional hole here or there, but not any glaring issues, although knowing that there were two more books to come kind of kept me from utter trepidation? As to characters, Parvin is an <i>interesting</i> MC. At first, she felt like an author-self-insert, which isn't bad, and later she felt like a reader-insert (?). It wasn't so bad as Divergent, where it feels like the characters are just there to serve the plot, and I think Parvin's personality really developed over the course of the story, but there were still hints of Parvin kind of serving the plot and theme a little bit. <br /><br />I'm not sure what to talk about next. I want to go into the worldbuilding some... first off, um, I've learned a new way to take off a character's <s>arm</s> hand. That entire culture was really unique and while a bit grotesque, I thought it was really interesting. I also pictured Willow like Saoirse Ronan from *cough* <i>Atonement</i>. The contrast between the West and East was good too. Also, I really don't know how to feel about Chase? Or Reid? But Jude is an epic character. &lt;3 And I think the potential-love-triangle typical of dystopian YA was handled pretty well? I don't think Parvin dealt with her attraction in so much of a namby-pamby way. And back to the worldbuilding, I think most of it was well-explained and the introduction of new elements was consistently smooth. The entire setting was pretty realistic, in my opinion, although we don't hear much about the origins of the wall or why? <s>oh and I would like to mention that the minute Solomon came onto the scene I immediately thought of Zash and thought "every author must have something they love to include in every book they write, perhaps this is it"</s> and I thought of yet another thing, which somehow didn't click for me until chapter thirty-six: radicals = irrational/infinite numbers. even besides the political meaning of the word, I thought this was really clever.<br /><br />That review meandered a lot, but suffice it to say I really did enjoy it. As a Christian, I think it was a breath of fresh air and did really well in that department, all things considered. While it's not what I might consider a comfort book in that it's particularly aesthetic (I would file <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40590407.Romanov" title="Romanov by Nadine Brandes" rel="nofollow noopener">Romanov</a> in the aesthetic category), it was at the same time <i>beautiful</i>. I would not hesitate to shed some bittersweet tears over this book, and I almost did many times. Much love to Nadine Brandes, she is such a light and inspiration to me ✨</span>
  <a data-text-id="7530308559386992961" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


